FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE - CHINA: SUSPECTED
***************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[In the original posting, the name of the city was erroneously written as
Wangyuan, it has been changed to Wanyuan in the corrected version
below. ProMED-mail regrets any inconveniences it may have caused through
this error. - Mod.MPP]


[1]
Date: Wed, 11 May 2005 11:53:35 +0800 (CST)
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Dajiyuan.com [translated by Mod.RY; edited]
<http://www.dajiyuan.com/gb/5/5/1/n906309.htm>


Taipingzen and Wangjiaxiang areas, both within the city boundary of
Wanyuan, Sichuan province, had a suspected outbreak of foot and mouth
disease (FMD). More than 200 pigs were destroyed by burning. The
authorities tried to suppress the news, but the rumors spread.

Dajiyuan News discovered that the outbreak was first heard of in
Wanjiaxiang on 20 Apr 2005. The signs include blisters, ulcers, and
pustules around the snouts of the pigs. Later, similar signs were found in
cattle.

Now no one dares to buy pork or beef. The municipal government set up a
disease control station. The bureau of farm animals convened several
closed-door meetings and decided to destroy more than 200 pigs and more
than 10 cattle and strictly blocked the news from the public.

People suspected it might be avian influenza and hoped for the World Health
Organization (WHO) to send a team of experts for an investigation.

The Dajiyuan News reporter had a telephone interview with 14 to 15 local
residents. Except 3 or 4 who had no idea about the matter, the majority of
the interviewees knew the story from hearsay.

The more precise date for the initial outbreak was 15 Apr 2005. The
epidemic then spread further between 15 and 20 Apr 2005 to involve Taiping,
Wanjiaxiang, Hualoufen, Chinhuazen, and Tchanfenxiang. As soon as people
heard about the epidemic, they dared not buy pork and switched to buying
chickens, ducks, and fish. The pork business has been affected gravely.
Some people found out from meat vendors that the affected pigs showed
blisters, ulcers, and pustulations. As to the cattle FMD, the signs were
less serious. People felt that the loss due to the epidemic was somewhat
serious in Wanyuan city.

It was said that in May and June 2004 a similar outbreak had occurred. That
[outbreak] lasted for about a month and resulted in destruction of 100 to
200 pigs. The disease control and prevention departments examined the case
and issued a formal public notification, saying no SARS or other suspicious
viruses were involved. Since then, people felt relieved and started to eat
pork again.

The government has not yet formally explained the current issue to the
public. For this reason, rumors are running wild among local residents.

Some say that pigs can contract FMD, referred to as "Number 5 Disease". It
not only acutely infects cattle, goats, sheep, and pigs -- resulting in
great losses to the pork industry -- but also is an epizootic disease,
meaning that humans are susceptible [this is incorrect; see moderator note
below - Mod.RY].

People who are used to eating pork have stopped. Some say that the color of
the pork is not right. Everyone hopes for clarification from the
authorities. Until then, people do not want to take the risk.

--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Humans are not susceptible to foot and mouth disease, which is caused by a
virus in the Picornaviridae family. Hand foot and mouth disease (HFMD), a
human disease, is often confused with the animal disease. But HFND is most
often caused by coxsackievirus A16 and less frequently by enterovirus 71 or
other enteroviruses. The enterovirus group also includes polioviruses,
coxsackieviruses, and echoviruses. The viruses that cause FMD are not
related to those that cause HFND.

Generally meat from FMD infected animals -- with thorough cooking -- is
considered safe for consumption. But transporting the animal to the
processing plant may spread the disease, which is why most infected animals
are not transported to a processing plant. - Mod.TG]

