[2]
Date: 11 May 2005
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: PlanetArk.com [edited]
<http://www.planetark.com/dailynewsstory.cfm/newsid/30747/story.htm>


China investigates talk of foot and mouth disease
-------------------------------------------------
The Chinese government is investigating rumours of an outbreak of the
highly contagious foot and mouth disease (FMD), an official from the
Agriculture Ministry said on Tuesday. Asked about talk in the grain trade
of an outbreak, the official in Beijing told Reuters that no cases had been
confirmed so far. "We are still investigating," he said without
elaborating. Traders in the soy market reported strong rumours that the
disease had spread in several provinces, but no further details were
available.

The Chinese government has not previously announced any outbreak of FMD,
which causes severe weight loss in cloven-hoofed animals like cattle and
hogs. But a Chinese government source said there was an outbreak of FMD
almost every year and that the government was currently working on a
reporting system. It had also advised the quarantine authorities to tighten
controls over exports after Hong Kong found FMD in beef from China, the
source said.

The animal health body Office International des Epizooties (OIE) lists
China as a country free of FMD, with vaccination. In 2001 an outbreak of
the disease in Britain devastated farming communities and was brought under
control only at a cost of an estimated GBP 8 billion (USD 15 billion).

--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Though it is true that animals can survive FMD, production drops
dramatically. The animals are in pain and do not want to walk or eat.
Consequently they lose weight, milk production drops, and of course feed
consumption decreases. The blisters and vesicles in the mouth and on the
hooves are quite painful. The infection can be transmitted on straw, feed
commodities, and on carcasses, and other animal products such as hides. We
look forward to hearing confirmation or exclusion of the diagnosis and
further information about the surveillance system proposed. - Mod.TG]
